            <h2 className="note-heading-page">Performance</h2>
            <div className="content-spacer-24">
              <div className="constraint-700">
                <p className="note-style-18">In this section we provide selected deep dives on particular aspects of performance we have found critical to having an impact with our health system partners. While these examples do not cover every dimension of performance that we monitor, each example illustrates how targeted evaluation helps drive clinically meaningful improvements both over current off-the-shelf models, and in our own system over time.</p>
              </div>

              <div className="content-spacer-64">
                <div className="content-spacer-32">
                  <p className="note-style-32">One of the core components of our product is our Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) system, which converts patient-clinician conversations into a transcript, which in turn, constitutes the key input to our note-generation system.</p>
                  <p className="note-style-18">Accurate transcription is critical to ensuring the quality of the final output, as well as an accurate record of the conversation that the clinician can reference later. <br>
                    <br>Our ASR models take the audio from a conversation as input, and produce several secondary outputs in addition to the transcript, including alignment of text to audio timestamps, and assignment of phrases to the relevant speaker (a process known as diarization). Here, we focus on our evaluation of the main output, the transcript itself.
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div className="content-spacer-48">
                  <div className="content-spacer-24">
                    <p className="note-style-32">Curating diverse data for evaluation</p>
                    <p className="note-style-18">In order to appropriately evaluate our transcription model, we need diverse data on clinical conversations, including audio and gold standard transcripts. To that end, we use several benchmark datasets, including:</p>
                  </div>
                  <div className="constraint-700">
                    <div className="note-2_2-block grey-bg">

                        <div data-faq-content="false" className="note-3_1-accordion-content" id="faq-content-0-2" style="max-height: 0px; opacity: 0; transform: translateY(20px); transition: max-height 300ms ease-out, opacity 300ms ease-out, transform 300ms ease-out;">
                          <div className="note-3_1-accordion-content-styles">
                            <p className="note-style-18 opacity-70">Such as the Librispeech benchmark dataset.</p>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div className="constraint-700">
              <div className="content-spacer-32">
                <div className="content-spacer-8">
                  <div className="note-style-18 opacity-50">PRIMER</div>
                  <div className="note-style-32">Metrics for assessing quality of clinical transcription</div>
                </div>
                <p className="note-style-18">To evaluate the quality of a transcript produced by an ASR system, we typically compare it to a gold standard reference transcript, written by a human listener.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div className="content-spacer-24">
                <div className="note-style-18 uppercase opacity-40">TWO IMPORTANT METRICS ARE:</div>
                <div className="note-3_1-metric-grid">
                  <div className="note-3_1-accordion">
                    <div data-w-id="ce63f5b3-cc17-4e34-86f2-26ada20bfb09" className="note-3_1-accordion-top">
                      <div>
                        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" fill="none">
                          <path d="M13.1283 13.5625L16.1914 10.5M16.1914 10.5L13.1283 7.4375M16.1914 10.5L8.31352 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                          <path d="M10.5013 16.1875L14.6955 11.9938C15.2468 11.4425 14.8564 10.5 14.0768 10.5L8.31157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                          <path d="M10.5013 4.8125L14.6955 9.00625C15.2468 9.55745 14.8564 10.5 14.0768 10.5L4.81157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                          <path d="M10.5013 16.1875L14.3221 12.3672C15.0111 11.6782 14.5232 10.5 13.5487 10.5L8.31157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                          <path d="M10.5013 4.8125L14.3221 8.63281C15.0111 9.32181 14.5231 10.5 13.5487 10.5L4.81157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                          <path d="M10.5013 16.1875L13.9486 12.7406C14.7755 11.9138 14.1899 10.5 13.0205 10.5L8.31157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                          <path d="M10.5013 4.8125L13.9486 8.25937C14.7755 9.08618 14.1899 10.5 13.0205 10.5L4.81157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                        </svg>
                      </div>
                      <div id="w-node-_9d7cc47f-1788-101f-7129-1ca989f24e7c-d4f3de5d" className="note-style-18-semibold uppercase">WORD ERROR RATE</div>
                    </div>
                    <div data-w-id="f039aa7e-de76-4db8-2398-12a95b1e0124" className="note-3_1-accordion-bottom" style="width: 489.773px;">
                      <div data-color-trigger="light" id="w-node-_7a6b0e30-e4f5-a323-9590-17b179c626d7-d4f3de5d" className="content-spacer-32">
                        <p className="note-style-18">Word error rate (WER) is calculated as the minimum number of word-level edits (substitutions, deletions, and insertions) to transform the reference transcript into the generated transcript, divided by the length of the reference transcript. <br>
                          <br>This calculation is illustrated in Example 1, where the transcript missed three words, and misunderstood one word (taken vs taking). Here, the minimum number of edits to correct the transcript is four: Adding back the three missing words, and correcting the misunderstood word. WER is calculated by dividing the number of edits by the length of the reference transcript, which contains 24 words, for a WER of 4 / 24 = 0.167.
                        </p>
                        <div>
                          <div className="note-3_1-calc-row note-style-20-semibold">
                            <div className="note-style-18-semibold">Number of edits</div>
                            <div className="note-style-18-semibold">4</div>
                          </div>
                          <div className="note-3_1-calc-row note-style-20-semibold cc-thick-line">
                            <div className="note-style-18-semibold">Length of reference transcript</div>
                            <div className="note-style-18-semibold">24</div>
                          </div>
                          <div className="note-3_1-calc-row note-style-20-semibold cc-no-line">
                            <div className="note-style-18-semibold">Word error rate</div>
                            <div className="note-style-18-semibold">0.167</div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                        <p className="note-style-18">However, as shown in the example above, not all errors are created equal. The patient mentions feeling pain in their back and the use of Advil. In general, correctly transcribing these medical terms is a top priority for an ASR system specialized for clinical text.</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div id="w-node-c9885e4a-000b-5791-aa25-e524ba5e4140-d4f3de5d" className="note-3_1-tab-component">
                    <div className="note-3_1-tab-explainer">

                      <div id="w-node-_1ff1e00b-c5ca-99c0-c134-9272c9b8a730-d4f3de5d" className="note-style-18-semibold uppercase">MEDICAL TERM RECALL RATE</div>
                    </div>
                    <div data-w-id="1ff1e00b-c5ca-99c0-c134-9272c9b8a732" className="note-3_1-accordion-bottom" style="width: 489.773px;">
                      <div id="w-node-_1ff1e00b-c5ca-99c0-c134-9272c9b8a733-d4f3de5d" className="content-spacer-32">
                        <p className="note-style-18">Medical term recall rate (MTR) serves the purpose of tracking more clinically meaningful errors, and is a complementary metric. MTR tracks the fraction of medical terms in the reference that are captured in the generated transcript. We continue with the example above to illustrate how this metric is calculated. <br>
                          <br>In this case, the words feeling, pain, back, and Advil are all medical terms, and since the generated transcript captured three out of four terms, the MTR would be 75%.
                        </p>
                        <p className="note-style-15 opacity-60">Example 1 (continued): MTR calculation with a simple example of a reference and generated transcript.</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>

                  <div className="note-style-32">Comparing to off-the-shelf transcription models</div>

                <p className="note-style-18">Since medical conversations have substantial overlap with generic conversations, we benchmark our ASR models on public datasets to ensure that we have comparable performance in the general conversation setting.                                           <div className="note-info-content">
                                            <p className="note-infor-paragraph">Shanafelt TD, West CP, Dyrbye LN, et al. Changes in Burnout and Satisfaction With Work-Life Integration in Physicians During the First 2 Years of the COVID-19 Pandemic. Mayo Clinic Proceedings. 12:2248-58. doi:10.1016/j.mayocp.2022.09.002. <br>
                                            </p>

                                        </dialog>
                                      </div>
                                    </div>
                                  </div>
                                  <p className="note-style-18">of physicians report burnout</p>
                                </div>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                          <div className="constraint-700">
                            <p className="note-style-18">Ambient documentation systems (or AI scribes) reduce documentation burden by drafting clinical notes based on raw audio of the clinical encounter. Clinicians edit and verify these notes before signing them in the Electronic Health Record (EHR). However, evaluation of these systems, and the quality of the documentation they draft, is complicated by the free-form nature of generated text and the various uses of clinical documentation. <br>
                              <br>This whitepaper describes our process for evaluating AI-generated documentation at Abridge, quantitative performance measures for many of our key systems, and our process for conducting holistic clinician-in-the-loop studies prior to green-lighting updated AI components into production. These evaluations have informed the development and deployment of our AI systems into deployment; systems that already process hundreds of thousands of clinical encounters every week, across dozens of health systems. By sharing our approach, we hope to foster greater transparency and facilitate dialogue among stakeholders in this fast-moving space.
                            </p>
                          </div>
                          <div className="_1-column-grid">

                          <h2 className="note-heading-page">quality and monitoring</h2>
                          <div className="constraint-700">
                            <p className="note-style-18">At the highest level, we can think of our clinical documentation engine as being comprised of two primary components: a world-class medically tailored speech recognition system and a note-generation system that transforms raw transcripts into drafted clinical notes.</p>

                                            <path strokeLinecap="butt" strokeLinejoin="miter" fillOpacity="0" strokeMiterlimit="10" stroke="rgb(0,0,0)" strokeOpacity="1" strokeWidth="2.021" d=" M0,3.2809998989105225 C1.812000036239624,3.2809998989105225 3.2809998989105225,1.812000036239624 3.2809998989105225,0 C3.2809998989105225,-1.812000036239624 1.812000036239624,-3.2809998989105225 0,-3.2809998989105225 C-1.812000036239624,-3.2809998989105225 -3.2809998989105225,-1.812000036239624 -3.2809998989105225,0 C-3.2809998989105225,1.812000036239624 -1.812000036239624,3.2809998989105225 0,3.2809998989105225z"></path>
                                          </g>
                                        </g>
                                      </g>
                                    </svg>
                                  </div>
                                  <div id="w-node-_2f13dfc3-6373-de0d-82f6-17841ce16b50-d4f3de5d" className="note-2-qm-text-block-wrap">
                                    <div id="w-node-_0e2905cf-594a-b423-a2a8-a2a9271a1cde-d4f3de5d" className="note-2-qm-text-block cc-02" style="will-change: opacity; opacity: 0;">
                                      <div className="note-style-32">Automated Speech Recognition (ASR)</div>
                                      <p className="note-style-18">The first component is our Automated Speech Recognition (ASR) system, which takes raw clinical audio and produces a transcript of the encounter.</p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div id="w-node-_5c345ad2-c17c-cd9c-84cb-8d2a68bded7c-d4f3de5d" className="note-2-qm-text-block cc-03" style="will-change: opacity; opacity: 0;">
                                      <div className="note-style-32">Note Generation</div>
                                      <p className="note-style-18">The second component is our note-generation system which uses the transcript to produce a draft of the clinical documentation.</p>
                                    </div>
                                  </div>
                                </div>
                                <p className="note-style-18">Each component uses a variety of underlying models. These are evaluated both individually and in an end-to-end fashion. We take a deliberate approach to evaluating and releasing upgrades to our core components:</p>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                          </div>

                              <path fillRule="evenodd" clipRule="evenodd" d="M0.759766 87.7999V75.0265L29.3223 46.706C37.7676 38.502 41.7998 33.9301 41.7998 26.9999C41.7998 23.5929 40.6115 20.7787 38.579 18.8153C36.5443 16.8498 33.6038 15.6799 29.9998 15.6799C26.0371 15.6799 22.7538 17.3144 20.4917 20.0542C18.2215 22.8038 16.9454 26.7122 17.1192 31.2895L17.1507 32.1199H1.49626L1.47994 31.3366C1.11101 13.6278 13.5722 0.639893 30.7198 0.639893C46.7391 0.639893 57.7998 11.8959 57.7998 26.3999C57.7998 39.1415 49.7267 47.4022 39.8068 56.8446L24.8952 72.6399H58.5198V87.7999H0.759766ZM23.0398 73.4399L39.2398 56.2799C49.1998 46.7999 56.9998 38.7599 56.9998 26.3999C56.9998 12.3599 46.3198 1.43989 30.7198 1.43989C14.0398 1.43989 1.91977 14.0399 2.27977 31.3199H16.3197C16.3095 31.0512 16.3042 30.7845 16.3035 30.5199C16.2817 21.4509 21.8379 14.8799 29.9998 14.8799C37.5598 14.8799 42.5998 19.7999 42.5998 26.9999C42.5998 34.3199 38.2798 39.1199 29.8798 47.2799L1.55977 75.3599V86.9999H57.7198V73.4399H23.0398Z" fill="currentColor"></path>
                              <path fillRule="evenodd" clipRule="evenodd" d="M117.797 2.19995V87.8H102.157V30.56H88.4766V16.24H93.9566C97.287 16.24 99.4682 15.5354 100.827 14.2284C102.178 12.9284 102.877 10.8767 102.877 7.79995V2.19995H117.797ZM102.957 29.76V87H116.997V2.99995H103.677V7.79995C103.677 14.16 100.797 17.04 93.9566 17.04H89.2766V29.76H102.957Z" fill="currentColor"></path>
                              <path fillRule="evenodd" clipRule="evenodd" d="M75.3195 72V87H90.6795V72H75.3195ZM74.5195 71.2H91.4795V87.8H74.5195V71.2Z" fill="currentColor"></path>
                            </svg>
                            <div className="note-subsection-header">
                              <h2 className="note-style-20 uppercase opacity-40">quality and monitoring</h2>
                              <p className="note-style-44-semibold-uppercase">Model development guided by automated metrics and clinician spot-checks</p>
                            </div>
                            <div className="constraint-700">
                              <div className="content-spacer-12">
                                <p className="note-style-32">Automated metrics as a screening tool for model development</p>
                                <p className="note-style-18">We rely on many automated metrics to guide early model development, using a large internal benchmark dataset containing clinical audio, gold standard transcripts, human-written reference notes, and rich metadata on patient characteristics. <br>
                                  <br>For our automatic speech recognition system, we use canonical metrics, including word error rate and medically tailored metrics (e.g., recall of medical terms), alongside more targeted analyses (e.g., capture of newly minted medication names). For our note-generation system, we compute automated metrics of quality that compare AI-generated and human-written summaries, including variants of precision and recall (e.g., of medical concepts), which serve as proxies for factuality and completeness. Throughout, we perform stratified analyses to assess performance across diverse patient subpopulations.
                                </p>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                            <div className="constraint-700">
                              <div className="content-spacer-12">
                                <p className="note-style-32">Clinician-driven spot-checks</p>
                                <p className="note-style-18">Throughout model development, Abridge clinicians spot-check notes generated on a curated set of encounters covering a range of clinical scenarios, providing both a coarse signal on difficult-to-measure aspects of quality and helping our modeling team develop intuition. This feedback is particularly important when a new model upgrade is meant to address a more subjective concern, such as incorporating certain stylistic preferences into note generation.</p>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      <div id="blinded-trials" chap-frac-num-trigger="2" className="note-content-inner w-node-_55ccbf21-137b-2aaf-cbcc-ac04d4e4bc0d-d4f3de5d">

                            <path fillRule="evenodd" clipRule="evenodd" d="M75.3195 72V87H90.6795V72H75.3195ZM74.5195 71.2H91.4795V87.8H74.5195V71.2Z" fill="currentColor"></path>
                          </svg>
                          <div className="note-subsection-header">
                            <h2 className="note-style-20 uppercase opacity-40">quality and monitoring</h2>
                            <p className="note-style-44-semibold-uppercase">Validation via blinded head-to-head trials Adjudicated by licensed clinicians</p>
                          </div>
                          <div className="constraint-700">
                            <p className="note-style-18">While automated metrics and clinician spot-checks are helpful to guide development of upgrades to our overall system, these metrics capture only a portion of the many salient dimensions of quality. Certifying a new system for deployment requires more than informal spot-checks.</p>

                            <p className="note-style-32">Before deploying models, we perform blinded, head-to-head evaluations with licensed clinicians as evaluators.</p>

                          <div className="constraint-700">
                            <p className="note-style-18">To this end, we developed a software platform that presents notes (one from the current system, the other from candidate systems) side-by-side, with clinical reviewers blinded to the system that authored each.</p>

                          <div className="constraint-700">
                            <div className="content-spacer-12">
                              <p className="note-style-18">To allow for early stopping when the results are conclusive, we use anytime-valid sequential hypothesis testing <sup>1</sup>, providing guarantees on the false positive rate that hold regardless of how long we run the trial. This approach provides strong statistical evidence for whether a proposed system is better (or worse) than its predecessor. </p>
                              <p className="note-disclaimer">1. Ramdas A. Foundations of Large-Scale Sequential Experimentation. In: KDD '19: Proceedings of the 25th ACM SIGKDD International Conference on Knowledge Discovery &amp; Data Mining. doi:10.1145/3292500.3332282</p>
                            </div>
                          </div>

                              <path fillRule="evenodd" clipRule="evenodd" d="M75.3195 72V87H90.6795V72H75.3195ZM74.5195 71.2H91.4795V87.8H74.5195V71.2Z" fill="currentColor"></path>
                            </svg>
                            <div className="note-subsection-header">
                              <h2 className="note-style-20 uppercase opacity-40">quality and monitoring</h2>
                              <p className="note-style-44-semibold-uppercase">Staged release process</p>
                            </div>
                            <div className="constraint-500">
                              <div className="content-spacer-12">
                                <p className="note-style-18">Even once our models survive a rigorous blinded test of clinician judgment, we take a careful staged-release approach to productionizing our models, verifying performance in vivo on selected cohorts prior to approving a broader release. <br>
                                  <br>The first stage is an alpha release with limited rollouts to specially trained early adopters. These clinicians are in frequent contact with Abridge staff and are trained to be especially vigilant about editing and comprehensive in their feedback. Only once we are satisfied that these users are better served by the improved model do we consider rolling out to wider audiences. <br>
                                  <br>At every stage of release, including full deployment, we continually collect both active feedback in the form of comments and star ratings, and passive feedback in the form of edits required to finalize the note, similar to the ongoing metrics we track during deployment as discussed below.
                                </p>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                            <div className="constraint-700"></div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div>

                            <div data-w-id="ac2fab82-73b9-d77a-e625-1b20308f6dc0" className="note-side-graphic-content-grid">
                              <div id="w-node-_6d137b07-109f-2795-8bfc-291297a133f8-d4f3de5d" className="note-left-column-sticky">
                                <div className="note-2_4-expand-black" style="will-change: width, height; width: 18px; height: 18px;"></div>
                              </div>
                              <div className="content-spacer-64">
                                <div className="constraint-700">
                                  <div className="content-spacer-24">
                                    <p className="note-style-18">Clinician-generated edits are inherently scalable as a feedback mechanism, as editing is already a natural workflow. These edits provide us with a rich signal for modeling purposes and enable the computation of high-level metrics to gauge how much editing is required. In addition, users have the option to provide quantitative ratings of note quality within the note-editing interface. <br>
                                      <br>These scalable quantitative metrics not only allow us to track ongoing real-world performance, but also provide us with sample sizes required to assess performance across diverse patient and provider subpopulations. Stratified evaluations require high-quality metadata (e.g., on patient demographics) that are not reliably captured in conversations, but can in many cases be pulled (with varying degrees of accuracy <sup>2</sup>) via integration with the EHR. <br>
                                      <br>We also develop model-driven proxies for meta-data that may not be captured in the medical record. For example, Abridge documents visits in a variety of languages, including visits that span multiple languages. Performing relevant language-stratified analyses requires that we can accurately identify which languages are spoken in each encounter.
                                    </p>
                                    <p className="note-disclaimer">2. Johnson JA, Moore B, Hwang EK, Hickner A, Yeo H. The accuracy of race &amp; ethnicity data in US based healthcare databases: A systematic review. The American Journal of Surgery. 10:463-70. doi:10.1016/j.amjsurg.2023.05.011.</p>
                                  </div>
                                </div>
                                <div className="constraint-700"></div>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                          <div>
                            <div className="content-spacer-64">
                              <div>
                                <h2 className="note-style-60 text-balance">Qualitative feedback for uncovering blind spots</h2>
                              </div>
                              <div page-color-trigger="dark" data-w-id="33a470df-6bf8-847d-5277-daa06d28f785" className="note-2_4-horizontal-track">
                                <div am-element="page-color" className="note-2_4-horizontal-sticky">
                                  <div className="note-2_4-horizontal-content" style="will-change: transform; transform: translate3d(0%, 0px, 0px) scale3d(1, 1, 1) rotateX(0deg) rotateY(0deg) rotateZ(0deg) skew(0deg, 0deg); transform-style: preserve-3d;">
                                    <div className="note-2_4-content-grid-first">
                                      <p className="note-style-18">Clinicians frequently provide free-text feedback, which plays an equally important role. Given the diversity of clinical encounters and open-endedness of note-drafting, blind spots are inevitable. Ensuring that concerns expressed in qualitative feedback are heard by model developers is essential for finding these blind spots and developing new tests to catch them in the future.</p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div className="note-2_4-content-grid-second">
                                      <div className="note-2_4-grid-second-b">
                                        <p className="note-style-15 opacity-60">To illustrate, consider the following real-world examples of issues that have been identified through open-ended feedback:</p>

                                          </svg>
                                          <div className="note-style-24-semibold">New medications are continuously being released</div>

                                        <div className="note-style-24-semibold">Clinicians and patients do not always agree</div>
                                        <p className="note-style-18 opacity-80">If a patient misstates their own diagnosis, and a clinician corrects them, is the conclusion appropriately reflected in the final note?</p>
                                      </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div className="note-2_4-content-grid-third">
                                      <p className="note-style-18-semibold">Customer feedback helps to identify these types of problems, and tracking of problem categories provides another mechanism for evaluating the efficacy of deployed patches. <br>
                                        <br>Qualitative feedback is also useful for eliciting stylistic preferencesone clinician may prefer that certain elements appear in the History of Present Illness (HPI) section, while another may prefer them in the Assessment &amp; Plan section.
                                      </p>
                                    </div>
                                  </div>
                                </div>
                              </div>
                              <div page-color-trigger="light" className="content-spacer-16">
                                <p className="note-style-32">Audits via dedicated tools</p>
                                <div className="constraint-700">
                                  <p className="note-style-18">Ongoing audits of note quality are essential for building and maintaining trust. However, audits can be inefficientto evaluate the appropriateness of a single note sentence, an evaluator must parse a long transcript of a conversation that they have never seen before. To aid in efficient review, we outfit all of our note viewers with a tool for pinpointing the relevant transcript excerpt. <br>
                                    <br>This same feature is available to our clinician users, helping them to verify the output of our system during the editing process.
                                  </p>
                                </div>

                          <h2 className="note-heading-page">Performance</h2>
                          <div className="content-spacer-24">
                            <div className="constraint-700">
                              <p className="note-style-18">In this section we provide selected deep dives on particular aspects of performance we have found critical to having an impact with our health system partners. While these examples do not cover every dimension of performance that we monitor, each example illustrates how targeted evaluation helps drive clinically meaningful improvements both over current off-the-shelf models, and in our own system over time.</p>

                            <div className="content-spacer-64">
                              <div className="content-spacer-32">
                                <p className="note-style-32">One of the core components of our product is our Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) system, which converts patient-clinician conversations into a transcript, which in turn, constitutes the key input to our note-generation system.</p>
                                <p className="note-style-18">Accurate transcription is critical to ensuring the quality of the final output, as well as an accurate record of the conversation that the clinician can reference later. <br>
                                  <br>Our ASR models take the audio from a conversation as input, and produce several secondary outputs in addition to the transcript, including alignment of text to audio timestamps, and assignment of phrases to the relevant speaker (a process known as diarization). Here, we focus on our evaluation of the main output, the transcript itself.
                                </p>
                              </div>
                              <div className="content-spacer-48">
                                <div className="content-spacer-24">
                                  <p className="note-style-32">Curating diverse data for evaluation</p>
                                  <p className="note-style-18">In order to appropriately evaluate our transcription model, we need diverse data on clinical conversations, including audio and gold standard transcripts. To that end, we use several benchmark datasets, including:</p>
                                </div>
                                <div className="constraint-700">
                                  <div className="note-2_2-block grey-bg">
                                    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="100%" viewBox="0 0 79 79" fill="none" className="note-2_2-icon _70">

                                      <path d="M24.1855 71.1821H22.9512V73.6509H24.1855V71.1821ZM24.1855 73.6509H53.8105V71.1821H24.1855V73.6509Z" fill="currentColor"></path>
                                      <path d="M27.4785 18.2699C27.4785 11.8156 32.6366 6.58337 38.9993 6.58337C45.3621 6.58337 50.5202 11.8156 50.5202 18.2699V42.6262C50.5202 49.0804 45.3621 54.3127 38.9993 54.3127C32.6366 54.3127 27.4785 49.0804 27.4785 42.6262V18.2699Z" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="2.46875"></path>

                                          <div id="w-node-f5e551f1-d7a4-0171-36b6-b8312c7e16d5-d4f3de5d" className="note-style-18-semibold">Standard research benchmark datasets</div>
                                        </div>
                                      </button>
                                      <div data-faq-content="false" className="note-3_1-accordion-content" id="faq-content-0-2" style="max-height: 0px; opacity: 0; transform: translateY(20px); transition: max-height 300ms ease-out, opacity 300ms ease-out, transform 300ms ease-out;">
                                        <div className="note-3_1-accordion-content-styles">
                                          <p className="note-style-18 opacity-70">Such as the Librispeech benchmark dataset.</p>

                                      </div>
                                    </div>
                                  </div>
                                </div>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                          <div className="constraint-700">
                            <div className="content-spacer-32">
                              <div className="content-spacer-8">
                                <div className="note-style-18 opacity-50">PRIMER</div>
                                <div className="note-style-32">Metrics for assessing quality of clinical transcription</div>
                              </div>
                              <p className="note-style-18">To evaluate the quality of a transcript produced by an ASR system, we typically compare it to a gold standard reference transcript, written by a human listener.</p>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                          <div>
                            <div className="content-spacer-24">
                              <div className="note-style-18 uppercase opacity-40">TWO IMPORTANT METRICS ARE:</div>
                              <div className="note-3_1-metric-grid">
                                <div className="note-3_1-accordion">
                                  <div data-w-id="ce63f5b3-cc17-4e34-86f2-26ada20bfb09" className="note-3_1-accordion-top">
                                    <div>
                                      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" fill="none">
                                        <path d="M13.1283 13.5625L16.1914 10.5M16.1914 10.5L13.1283 7.4375M16.1914 10.5L8.31352 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                        <path d="M10.5013 16.1875L14.6955 11.9938C15.2468 11.4425 14.8564 10.5 14.0768 10.5L8.31157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                        <path d="M10.5013 4.8125L14.6955 9.00625C15.2468 9.55745 14.8564 10.5 14.0768 10.5L4.81157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                        <path d="M10.5013 16.1875L14.3221 12.3672C15.0111 11.6782 14.5232 10.5 13.5487 10.5L8.31157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                        <path d="M10.5013 4.8125L14.3221 8.63281C15.0111 9.32181 14.5231 10.5 13.5487 10.5L4.81157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                        <path d="M10.5013 16.1875L13.9486 12.7406C14.7755 11.9138 14.1899 10.5 13.0205 10.5L8.31157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                        <path d="M10.5013 4.8125L13.9486 8.25937C14.7755 9.08618 14.1899 10.5 13.0205 10.5L4.81157 10.5" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="0.875" strokeLinecap="square"></path>
                                      </svg>
                                    </div>
                                    <div id="w-node-_9d7cc47f-1788-101f-7129-1ca989f24e7c-d4f3de5d" className="note-style-18-semibold uppercase">WORD ERROR RATE</div>
                                  </div>
                                  <div data-w-id="f039aa7e-de76-4db8-2398-12a95b1e0124" className="note-3_1-accordion-bottom" style="width: 489.773px;">
                                    <div data-color-trigger="light" id="w-node-_7a6b0e30-e4f5-a323-9590-17b179c626d7-d4f3de5d" className="content-spacer-32">
                                      <p className="note-style-18">Word error rate (WER) is calculated as the minimum number of word-level edits (substitutions, deletions, and insertions) to transform the reference transcript into the generated transcript, divided by the length of the reference transcript. <br>
                                        <br>This calculation is illustrated in Example 1, where the transcript missed three words, and misunderstood one word (taken vs taking). Here, the minimum number of edits to correct the transcript is four: Adding back the three missing words, and correcting the misunderstood word. WER is calculated by dividing the number of edits by the length of the reference transcript, which contains 24 words, for a WER of 4 / 24 = 0.167.
                                      </p>
                                      <div>
                                        <div className="note-3_1-calc-row note-style-20-semibold">
                                          <div className="note-style-18-semibold">Number of edits</div>
                                          <div className="note-style-18-semibold">4</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div className="note-3_1-calc-row note-style-20-semibold cc-thick-line">
                                          <div className="note-style-18-semibold">Length of reference transcript</div>
                                          <div className="note-style-18-semibold">24</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div className="note-3_1-calc-row note-style-20-semibold cc-no-line">
                                          <div className="note-style-18-semibold">Word error rate</div>
                                          <div className="note-style-18-semibold">0.167</div>
                                        </div>
                                      </div>
                                      <p className="note-style-18">However, as shown in the example above, not all errors are created equal. The patient mentions feeling pain in their back and the use of Advil. In general, correctly transcribing these medical terms is a top priority for an ASR system specialized for clinical text.</p>
                                    </div>
                                  </div>
                                </div>
                                <div id="w-node-c9885e4a-000b-5791-aa25-e524ba5e4140-d4f3de5d" className="note-3_1-tab-component">

                                    <div id="w-node-_1ff1e00b-c5ca-99c0-c134-9272c9b8a730-d4f3de5d" className="note-style-18-semibold uppercase">MEDICAL TERM RECALL RATE</div>
                                  </div>
                                  <div data-w-id="1ff1e00b-c5ca-99c0-c134-9272c9b8a732" className="note-3_1-accordion-bottom" style="width: 489.773px;">
                                    <div id="w-node-_1ff1e00b-c5ca-99c0-c134-9272c9b8a733-d4f3de5d" className="content-spacer-32">
                                      <p className="note-style-18">Medical term recall rate (MTR) serves the purpose of tracking more clinically meaningful errors, and is a complementary metric. MTR tracks the fraction of medical terms in the reference that are captured in the generated transcript. We continue with the example above to illustrate how this metric is calculated. <br>
                                        <br>In this case, the words feeling, pain, back, and Advil are all medical terms, and since the generated transcript captured three out of four terms, the MTR would be 75%.
                                      </p>
                                      <p className="note-style-15 opacity-60">Example 1 (continued): MTR calculation with a simple example of a reference and generated transcript.</p>
                                    </div>
                                  </div>

                                <div className="note-style-32">Comparing to off-the-shelf transcription models</div>

                              <p className="note-style-18">Since medical conversations have substantial overlap with generic conversations, we benchmark our ASR models on public datasets to ensure that we have comparable performance in the general conversation setting.                             <div className="content-spacer-24 margin">
                              <p className="note-style-32">Internal multilingual evaluation of our ASR and note-generation system</p>
                              <p className="note-style-18">We start by discussing the evaluations we have used to benchmark our multilingual performance internally, and which have formed the basis for model improvements that drive our real-world multilingual performance, described at the end of this deep dive. <br>
                                <br>First, our approved set of languages is based on the observed performance of our ASR system on audio and associated gold standard transcripts from a variety of languages. One of the datasets we use in evaluation is FLEURS, a parallel speech dataset in 102 languages built on top of the machine translation FLoRes-101 benchmark. Here we have access to gold standard transcripts, which allows us to establish ASR performance by measuring WER. <br>
                                <br>Measured on this dataset, for three of the non-English languages that we support, our WER is even lower in that language, compared to English:
                              </p>

                              <p className="note-style-18">The primary metric for the end-to-end evaluation of our system is quantitative ratings of note quality (or star ratings) that users provide within the note editing interface, giving a rating from 1 to 5. This feedback lends itself to straightforward metrics (e.g., tracking the average star rating over time), and tracking performance across categories of encounters. <br>
                                <br>For reference, over the last three months (May-July), we collected tens of thousands of star ratings, with an average rating of 4.3 out of 5 for English-language encounters. &nbsp;Meanwhile, our performance in our most frequent non-English languages is nearly as strong over the same time period.
